Brian Moynihan, Bank of America Chief, Got 23% Pay Raise in 2015

By MICHAEL CORKERYFEB. 12, 2016



Continue reading the main story
Share This Page

Continue reading the main story










Photo






Brian Moynihan, chief executive of Bank of America, made $16 million last year, a raise that reflected the bank’s improved performance.

Credit
            Bobby Yip/Reuters        



Bank of America gave its chief executive, Brian T. Moynihan, a pay package last year that was 23 percent larger than in 2014, as the big bank generated higher profits and put its mortgage problems squarely behind it.Mr. Moynihan’s $16 million pay package includes a $1.5 million cash salary and $14.5 million in restricted stock awards tied to certain performance goals. The package does not include a cash bonus.In 2014, a year in which the bank, based in Charlotte, N.C., paid billions of dollars to settle investigations into its sale of faulty mortgage securities, Mr. Moynihan received a $13 million pay package.The Bank of America board’s decision to increase Mr. Moynihan’s pay package reflects the bank’s improved performance in 2015, as it increased its capital levels and generated $16 billion in profit compared with $4.8 billion in 2014.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Last year, Mr. Moynihan also survived a campaign by some shareholders to strip him of his title of bank chairman. Continue reading the main story







Advertisement

Continue reading the main story





“Bank of America in 2015 demonstrated continued progress as a result of its strategy of simplifying the company,” the company said in a securities filing late Friday that detailed Mr. Moynihan’s compensation.
Newsletter Sign Up
Continue reading the main story

  


